## Stack

- **Backend:** Grails [x.y], Groovy, GORM (Hibernate), Spock, CodeNarc.
- **Frontend:** GSP views rendered server-side, vanilla JavaScript
  (`grails-app/assets/javascripts/`), semantic HTML5 — no SPA framework.
- **Build:** Gradle wrapper (`./gradlew`).

## Non-negotiable rules

- No code change begins before `docs/specs/spec.md` reflects it.
- Every business rule has an ID (`BR-1`, `BR-2`, ...) assigned in the spec
  before it is implemented.
- Every BR has at least one Spock feature method named
  `"BR-n: <short description>"`.
- Commits that implement or fix a BR cite its ID in the commit message.
- Business-rule logic lives in the **service layer only**
  (`grails-app/services/`), annotated `@Transactional` where it mutates
  state. Controllers (`grails-app/controllers/`) parse input, call a
  service, and `render`/`respond` — they never call `.save()` or mutate a
  domain instance directly.
- GORM domain classes (`grails-app/domain/`) declare `constraints` for every
  field that has a validation rule in the spec — don't enforce a BR only in
  Groovy code when a GORM constraint can express it.
- All dynamic values rendered into GSP go through Grails' auto-encoding
  (`encodeAsHTML()` / the `<%= %>` default) — no `raw()` on user-supplied or
  BR-relevant data without an explicit, reviewed reason.
- Zero CodeNarc violations on changed files (`./gradlew codenarcMain
  codenarcTest`).
- No hardcoded credentials/API keys/connection strings — externalize via
  environment variables or a secrets manager (`docs/standards/security-standard.md`
  §3). No dependency with a known `HIGH`/`CRITICAL` CVE ships
  (`./gradlew dependencyCheckAnalyze`).

